        privateMethod();
    }

    private void _privateMethod() {
        // implementation
    }
}
```

In this example, the underscore character is used to indicate that `_privateMethod()` is a private method within the `ExampleInterface` interface. This is a new feature in Java 9 and is part of the reason why the underscore character is now considered a keyword and cannot be used as an identifier.

To summarize, the underscore character '_' is a keyword in Java 9 and later versions, and cannot be used as an identifier. This change was introduced to support private interface methods, which is a new feature in Java 9. When working with Java 9 or later versions, it is important to be aware of this change and avoid using the underscore character in identifiers to prevent compilation errors.

